To set up I2C decode on a Tektronix MSO4/5/6 Series oscilloscope using pyvisa backend, you typically use the SCOPE's command interface to configure the bus decode. For I2C, you need to specify the bus type, assign the clock and data channels, and enable the bus.

Below is a TekAutomate Steps UI flow that does this. Note: The actual SCPI commands for bus setup are based on Tektronix documentation, but please verify on your instrument as command syntax may vary slightly.

```json
{
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "connect",
      "id": "connect_scope",
      "title": "Connect to Scope"
    },
    {
      "type": "comment",
      "id": "comment_i2c",
      "title": "Set up I2C decode on B1: CH1=Clock, CH2=Data"
    },
    {
      "type": "write",
      "id": "bus_define",
      "title": "Define I2C Bus B1",
      "params": {
        "command": "BUS1:TYPE IIC"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "write",
      "id": "bus_clock",
      "title": "Set I2C Clock to CH1",
      "params": {
        "command": "BUS1:IIC:SCL CH1"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "write",
      "id": "bus_data",
      "title": "Set I2C Data to CH2",
      "params": {
        "command": "BUS1:IIC:SDA CH2"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "write",
      "id": "bus_enable",
      "title": "Enable I2C Bus B1",
      "params": {
        "command": "BUS1:STATE ON"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "disconnect",
      "id": "disconnect_scope",
      "title": "Disconnect from Scope"
    }
  ]
}
```

This flow:
1. Connects to the scope.
2. Adds a comment for clarity.
3. Sets BUS1 to I2C decode.
4. Assigns CH1 as SCL (clock).
5. Assigns CH2 as SDA (data).
6. Enables the bus decode.
7. Disconnects from the scope.

Let me know if you want to add waveform capture or save steps!

